---
import ArticleLayout from '../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
import { localizedPath } from '../../i18n/utils';

const locale = 'en';
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="About WorthCalc"
  description="WorthCalc is a free set of browser-based calculators that answer one question: is it actually worth it?"
  locale={locale}
  updated="2026-07-15"
  alternateLocales={['en', 'zh', 'es', 'fr', 'de']}
>
  <p>
    WorthCalc exists because most "is it worth it" questions get answered with
    gut feeling instead of arithmetic. Is that 0% installment plan actually
    free? Are your subscriptions quietly eating a month's rent every year?
    Would a Costco membership pay for itself at your spending level? These are
    math problems, not opinions — so we built calculators instead of writing
    another listicle.
  </p>
  <p>
    Every tool on this site runs entirely in your browser. There is no backend
    that receives the numbers you type in — no account, no upload, no server
    round-trip. You can check the math, close the tab, and nothing you entered
    ever leaves your device (aside from anything you explicitly choose to save
    locally for next time).
  </p>
  <p>
    We currently publish eight calculators covering everyday money decisions:
    true APR on installment and BNPL plans, subscription cost audits, Costco
    membership break-even, EV vs. gas total cost of ownership, rent vs. buy,
    commute cost comparison, the "latte factor" daily habit calculator, and
    cashback credit card break-even. Each one is free, ad-supported, and
    built to give you a plain verdict — not just a pile of numbers.
  </p>
  <p>
    WorthCalc is independently run. We are not a bank, lender, brokerage, or
    financial advisor, and nothing on this site is investment or financial
    advice — see our <a href={localizedPath(locale, '/disclaimer')}>disclaimer</a> for details.
    If you spot a calculation that looks wrong or have a tool idea, reach us at
    the address on the <a href={localizedPath(locale, '/contact')}>contact page</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The calculators simplify real-world choices into estimates. They cannot
    know your full financial situation, local taxes, contract terms, credit
    profile, risk tolerance, or future price changes. For major decisions
    involving debt, housing, taxes, insurance, investments, or legal rights,
    please confirm the current terms and speak with a qualified professional.
  </p>
  <h2>How we build and review a calculator</h2>
  <p>
    Every calculator starts by separating the question into five parts: user
    inputs, formulas, editable assumptions, outputs, and limitations. Default
    numbers demonstrate the interface; they are not market averages or personal
    recommendations. Before making a decision, replace them with your own bill,
    contract, or current quote. Each tool page publishes its methodology,
    assumptions, worked example, limitations, and last-reviewed date so you can
    trace how the result was produced instead of accepting a verdict on faith.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before publication, we test at least three kinds of cases: a normal input,
    a boundary close to zero or break-even, and an extreme input that could make
    the result invalid. We also check mobile controls, input labels, estimate
    language, and exported results. When a tool depends on interest rates,
    membership fees, taxes, reward rules, or product terms, the page must state
    that those external conditions can change and that the current official
    terms still need to be verified.
  </p>

  <h2>What the result cannot decide for you</h2>
  <p>
    A calculator compares only the factors you enter. It does not know your
    emergency savings, job stability, family obligations, health needs, credit
    profile, or risk tolerance. A result that looks favorable still needs a
    cash-flow, exit-cost, and worst-case check. An unfavorable result does not
    mean convenience, time, accessibility, or quality of life has no value.
    WorthCalc makes assumptions visible; the final decision remains yours.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>
